channel.title: Interleaved RSS Feed
channel.description: This is an interleaved feed of the most recent entries from each RSS source, skipping any feeds with errors.

item.title: Disney's Blockbusters Can't Smooth Parks' Rough Ride
item.description: Weakening consumer spending is hurting the Mouse House in its most profitable business: theme parks.

item.title: Uber reports better-than-expected earnings and revenue for second quarter
item.description: Uber reported earnings and revenue that topped estimates for its second quarter.

item.title: U.S. Crude Oil Inventories Fall for Sixth Straight Week
item.description: U.S. crude oil inventories fell for a sixth consecutive week, dropping by 3.7 million barrels, while product stocks rose as refineries increased their capacity use.

item.title: Here's why Eli Lilly is down heading into earnings — and how we plan to play it
item.description: The Investing Club holds its "Morning Meeting" every weekday at 10:20 a.m. ET.

item.title: Credit-Card Autopay Can Benefit Consumers (a Little)
item.description: New research suggests nudging consumers to automatically pay off credit-card balances can get complicated.

item.title: Sunrun sees market opportunity after SunPower files for bankruptcy, company's shares surge
item.description: Sunrun posted a surprise profit and sees opportunity to gain market share.

item.title: Regulators Probing Big Banks' Handling of Zelle Scams
item.description: Investigation examines whether JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, Wells Fargo and others do enough to shut down accounts controlled by bad actors.

item.title: Disney beats estimates as combined streaming services turn a profit
item.description: Disney beat estimates as its combined streaming businesses — Disney+, Hulu and ESPN+ — turned a profit for the first time.

item.title: What Market Upheaval? Companies Are Selling Debt Just Fine
item.description: Corporate bond prices and issuance are recovering after the recent rout.

item.title: CVS slashes profit guidance, will cut $2 billion in expenses as insurance costs climb
item.description: CVS said higher medical costs are weighing on its insurance business, and announced Aetna President Brian Kane will step down.
